            <!-- Improve access -->
            <h2 id="improve-voting">Improve access to voting</h2>
            <p>There are a five states (Colorado, Hawaii, Oregon, Washington and Utah) that allow <a href="https://www.ncsl.org/research/elections-and-campaigns/all-mail-elections.aspx" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">all-mail elections</a> (otherwise known as vote-by-mail), with 21 others that provide vote-by-mail for smaller elections. Additionally, all states have some form of <a href="https://www.ncsl.org/research/elections-and-campaigns/absentee-and-early-voting.aspx" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">absentee ballots and early voting</a> available to voters, but there is room to expand this - including the creation of a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Election_Day_(United_States)" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">holiday for Election Day</a>.</p>
            <p>Contact your <a href="https://www.usa.gov/election-office" alt="" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">local election officials</a> to see if you can implement vote-by-mail, early voting, and absentee ballots for the smallest elections possible, and scale up from there. If you can get official support all the way up to the county level, you have a chance of changing the laws in your state!</p>
